         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">25, WILTON PLACE, S.W. ¶ March 1866 ¶ My dear Sir ¶  ¶ Your second box of Compositae (Aster etc) has safely arrived per Yorkshire and has reached Kew. ¶  ¶ Your letter of the 25th Decr ¶  reached me t...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">66.03.19</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M4, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text" style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times, Times; ">25, WILTON PLACE, S.W.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">March 1866<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Since the last part of th</seg>
                     <seg style="">e letter is dated 19 March, the letter as a whole has been assigned this date on the basis that this was when Bentham finished writing it. </seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your second box of <name key="Compositae">Compositae</name> (<name key="Aster">Aster</name> etc) has safely arrived per Yorkshire and has reached Kew.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your letter of the 25th Decr<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M to G. Bentham, 25 December 1865 (in this edition as 65-12-25d).</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> reached me the day after last post day — In reply I find I cannot dispense with <name key="Compositae">Compositae</name> for the third volume — and I must say considering my age and the consequent precariousness of my life it is better that I should proceed as far as I can with the Flora which must in the first instance be worked up in this country for the sake of identifying old species, than to delay it for supplements which are the less wanted as you have been publishing the novelties to be added in your Fragmenta — and which at any rate you can do at least as well as myself.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</name> and <name key="Laurineae">Laurineae</name> under our arrangement cannot possibly come into the third volume — and besides it would be very inconsiderate to meddle with <name key="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</name> till the volume of the Prodromus now printing is out.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>J. Müller (1866).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Melaleuca you sent a specimen of from the Melbourne garden as M. Moorei is the commonest form of M. pentagona (with narrow leaves)<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In his letter of 25 December to which Bentham is responding, M asked </seg>for the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Melaleuca</seg> he had sent to be named, if new, for Dr William McCrae, not for anyone named Moore. No <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Melaleuca</seg> species named for either McCrea or Moore is listed in APNI (accessed 4 July 2020).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Eugenias will be returned in a box now packing with <name key="Umbelliferae">Umbelliferae</name>
               <name key="Araliaceae">Araliaceae</name> etc. I have not altered the E. Wilsoni<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">E. Wilsonii</seg>
                     <seg style="">?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I fear it is too late now to alter <name key="Eucalyptus%20diversicolor">Eucalyptus diversicolor</name> into E. colossea — the former name being published in your Fragmenta will be adopted by botanists whatever name may be subsequently given to it and a new name would only add to the confusion of the overcharged synonymy.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You send a plant as Homalium ?pentandrum.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The name <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Homalium%20pentandrum">Homalium pentandrum</name>
                     </seg> could not be found (APNI, accessed 4 July 2020).</p>
               </note> I find the ovary <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">2-celled</hi>
               </seg> with 2 <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">erect</hi>
               </seg> ovules in each cell. It appears to me to be a Celastrus very near C. bilocularis but a little different in petals and inflorescence, the specimen is however not sufficient to speak with certainty</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I put <name key="Astrotriche">Astrotriche</name> in <name key="Araliaceae">Araliaceae</name> but cannot agree with Seemann in removing <name key="Hydrocotyle">Hydrocotyle</name> from <name key="Umbelliferae">Umbelliferae</name>.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Seemann (1863), pp. 278-80. </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your <name key="Mackinlaya">Mackinlaya</name> is I think a very good genus although monotypic — but <name key="Irvingia">Irvingia</name> is much better in Hedera where you first put it. As to what Seemann says of the ovary being more inferior than in <name key="Hedera%20helix">Hedera helix</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Seemann (1865), p. 201, note.</p>
               </note>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I have had vertical sections of the two side by side without detecting the slightest difference in this respect. — Seemann has a good deal of cleverness and writes well but dissects very little and takes a good deal upon credit or from external examination.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">19th March</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The box I mentioned was sent off a few days ago. I presume the bill of lading will be sent to you this mail.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I must beg you to make one correction in the <name key="Umbelliferae">Umbelliferae</name> — It having been shown that Didiscus DC (including Dimetopia) is the true Trachymene Rudge I was obliged to adopt that name but I had overlooked that <name key="Dimetopia%20pusilla">Dimetopia pusilla</name> is <name key="Trachymene%20pilosa">Trachymene pilosa</name> Sm. consequently <name key="Didiscus%20pilosa">Didiscus pilosa</name> which I had called T. pilosa must have another specific name and I have now called it T. australis</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have finished the greater part of <name key="Rubiaceae">Rubiaceae</name> and hope to get through the remainder this week so as to commence upon <name key="Compositae">Compositae</name> next week</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I took the <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name> to the printers three days since and hope to have already three or four sheets to send you next mail — after the first fortnight I expect to get two sheets a week through the press</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Yours very sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Bentham</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dr Mueller<space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I trust if the remaining <name key="Compositae">Compositae</name> are not yet sent off you will kindly do so immediately in order not to delay the volume.</p>
